      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Van Lathan on ‘Nope’",
      "note": "spoiler-free, then spoilers",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Nope",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "Kaluuya and Keke Palmer as siblings running a Hollywood horse ranch who try to film the thing in the sky. Van finds the first third clunky and Shyamalan-esque, warmer on it the more he sits with it; both flag that the crowd-pleasing win at the end undercuts the movie's own warning about profiting off nature. Shot on IMAX by Hoyte van Hoytema, scored by Michael Abels, cut by Nicholas Monsour."
        },
        {
          "title": "Get Out",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "The point of comparison both keep returning to. Van was a skeptic before release, then it blew him away; the pair credit it with making Peele a brand and reviving original studio horror."
        },
        {
          "title": "Us",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Van didn't like it. Beautiful to look at, but more a museum than an experience, and it strains toward its final reveal. Sean thinks it works better as an episode than a single sitting."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Jordan Peele on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Nope",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "Peele on wanting a massive film, inventing horse trainer Otis Sr.'s fake career to get a 'Berenstain Bears' collapse of real and invented history, and building the chimp set 30% larger so Terry Notary's performance would read smaller. His line: people like movies more than messages."
        },
        {
          "title": "Scream",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "Peele's answer to the show's closing question, the last great thing he's seen, partly because it gave him a shout-out."
        }
      ]
    }
